2.2 Role of BountyAdapter.sol
BountyAdapter is a thin facade contract. It doesn't hold funds and has no escrow logic of its own. Its job: add bounty-board-specific semantics (categories, tags, IPFS descriptions) on top of ERC-8183 jobs, and integrate ERC-8004 reputation checks.


// Simplified structure of BountyAdapter.sol

contract BountyAdapter {
    address public constant AGENTIC_COMMERCE =
        0x0747EEf0706327138c69792bF28Cd525089e4583;
    address public constant IDENTITY_REGISTRY =
        0x8004A818BFB912233c491871b3d84c89A494BD9e;
    address public constant REPUTATION_REGISTRY =
        0x8004B663056A597Dffe9eCcC1965A193B7388713;

    struct BountyMeta {
        uint256 jobId;          // ERC-8183 job ID
        string  ipfsDescHash;   // Full description on IPFS
        string  category;       // 'dev' | 'design' | 'content' | 'data' | 'other'
        string[] tags;          // ['solidity', 'arc', 'typescript']
        uint256 agentId;        // ERC-8004 agentId of the worker (0 if human)
        bool    agentOnly;      // true = only AI agents may take it
    }

    mapping(uint256 => BountyMeta) public bounties; // jobId => meta
    uint256[] public allJobIds;                      // list of all bounties
}


2.3 Bounty lifecycle
Status	Who can transition it	Description
OPEN	Anyone / agent	Bounty created, waiting for a worker
ASSIGNED	—	Worker took the task (setBudget called)
FUNDED	—	Poster deposited USDC into the ERC-8183 escrow
SUBMITTED	—	Worker submitted the result (IPFS hash)
COMPLETED	Poster / evaluator	Result approved, USDC sent to the worker
EXPIRED	Automatic	Deadline passed, USDC refunded to the poster
REJECTED	Poster / evaluator	Result rejected, re-submit possible (v2)

